# Working with .maxpat Files

`.maxpat` files are verbose JSON (up to 68K lines) — do NOT read them directly. Use the analyzer tool instead.

## Before touching any .maxpat file

Run the analyzer to get a compact summary:

```bash
# Quick overview (root level only, no comments)
python scripts/analyze_maxpat.py <file>.maxpat --depth 0 --no-comments

# Full logical structure
python scripts/analyze_maxpat.py <file>.maxpat --no-comments

# Just messaging topology (fastest for understanding signal flow)
python scripts/analyze_maxpat.py <file>.maxpat --sends-only

# Save to file for reference
python scripts/analyze_maxpat.py <file>.maxpat --no-comments -o /tmp/<file>_summary.txt
```

## Output format

- `obj-N  <text>  [inlets in, outlets out]` — one line per object
- `obj-A:outlet -> obj-B:inlet` — patch cord connections
- Subpatchers shown as indented sections
- Send/Receive map at the bottom with send-only / receive-only cross-reference
- External References: bpatchers and js/v8 scripts

## Key facts about this patch

- Inter-patch messaging uses `send`/`receive` with namespaced names (e.g. `#1[pl]stop`, `tr_pulse`, `kmod`)
- `#1` is a Max argument placeholder — becomes the channel number (1–8) at instantiation
- `bpatcher` boxes embed another `.maxpat` by filename; they do NOT inline their contents
- Subpatchers (`p <name>`) inline their full graph inside the parent box JSON
- `s` / `r` are shorthand for `send` / `receive`; `s~` / `r~` are audio-rate variants
